From e0f48b5fc068e607461359e43aee03e218cab183 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 20:41:41 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] feat(backend-readiness): enforce apiClient boundary, real
 streamJob polling, close parseResponse gap (Phase 6)

- eslint.config.mjs: added a scoped rule banning direct fetch() in
  src/components/**  and src/hooks/** (0 violations found -- the
  boundary was already respected in practice, now it's enforced).
- Found parseResponse() was called at ZERO of ~35 apiClient call
  sites -- completely unused despite existing. Retrofitted it at 4
  verified call sites (useBomConversion.ts x2, VendorIngestionDesk.tsx)
  where the response type is a confirmed z.infer of the matching
  schema. Left the other ~30 as an explicit scoped follow-up rather
  than a blind sweep -- spot-checking found /api/boq/ingest's actual
  response shape (BoqResponsePayload) doesn't match the 'obvious'
  IngestResponseSchema, same landmine pattern as Phase 3b.
- Fixed 12 test files whose apiClient mocks were missing
  parseResponse entirely (would TypeError the moment any covered
  code path calls it) -- only 1 was actually broken by this round's
  changes, fixed all 12 proactively to remove the landmine for any
  future parseResponse work.
- apiClient.ts: replaced streamJob()'s single GET-dressed-as-SSE with
  genuine interval-based polling that keeps polling until a terminal
  status. JobStreamer.tsx needs zero changes -- same onMessage/
  onError/close interface, real implementation behind it now.
- workflowHandlers.ts: GET /api/jobs/:id now tracks real incremental
  progress per job id across polls (25/55/80/completed) instead of
  always returning 'completed' on the first call -- otherwise the new
  polling would have nothing genuine to observe. Confirmed server.ts's
  real job endpoint already does this identical increment-per-poll
  pattern independently, which is strong evidence polling (not push)
  is what this codebase actually converged on at every layer, not a
  legacy fallback -- see the plan doc for the full reasoning.
- Rewrote apiClient.test.ts's 2 streamJob tests that were locking in
  the old one-shot-GET behavior; added coverage proving multiple
  genuine polls happen and stop exactly at the terminal status.
- Found and fixed a real react-hooks/refs lint ERROR introduced in
  Phase 4 (reading overlayRef.current during render inside useMemo) --
  only caught because this was the first phase eslint was actually
  run, not just tsc --noEmit. Refactored the graph overlay from a ref
  to real useState; fixed a related cascading-render warning using
  React's documented render-time state-adjustment pattern. No other
  errors found in Phases 0-5's code when eslint finally ran across
  all of it, but that was unverified luck until now, not something
  actually checked at the time.

Verified: tsc --noEmit clean, eslint src clean (0 errors, 140
pre-existing warnings none of which are new), full vitest suite
green (85 files / 401 tests, 0 regressions).
